  "local_port": 35864,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What do I eat on the Ketogenics Diet?",
  "response": "The **Ketogenic (Keto) Diet** is a high-fat, moderate-protein, and very low-carbohydrate eating plan designed to put your body into a state of **ketosis**, where it burns fat for fuel instead of carbohydrates. Here\u2019s a detailed guide on what to eat on the Keto Diet:\n\n---\n\n### **Foods to Eat on the Keto Diet**\n1. **Healthy Fats** (70-80% of daily calories)  \n   - Avocados and avocado oil  \n   - Olive oil, coconut oil, and MCT oil  \n   - Butter and ghee (preferably grass-fed)  \n   - Animal fats (e.g., lard, tallow)  \n   - Nuts and seeds (in moderation): almonds, walnuts, chia seeds, flaxseeds, etc.  \n\n2. **Protein** (20-25% of daily calories)  \n   - Fatty cuts of meat: beef, pork, lamb  \n   - Poultry: chicken, turkey, duck (with skin)  \n   - Fish: salmon, mackerel, sardines, tuna (fattier varieties are best)  \n   - Shellfish: shrimp, crab, lobster, oysters  \n   - Eggs (whole eggs are ideal)  \n   - Organ meats: liver, heart, kidney  \n\n3. **Low-Carb Vegetables** (5-10% of daily calories)  \n   - Leafy greens: spinach, kale, arugula, lettuce  \n   - Cruciferous vegetables: broccoli, cauliflower, Brussels sprouts, cabbage  \n   - Zucchini, asparagus, green beans, bell peppers, and mushrooms  \n   - Avocado (technically a fruit, but included here due to its low carb content)  \n\n4. **Dairy** (choose full-fat options)  \n   - Cheese: cheddar, mozzarella, goat cheese, cream cheese, blue cheese  \n   - Heavy cream and sour cream  \n   - Unsweetened Greek yogurt (in moderation)  \n   - Butter and ghee  \n\n5. **Beverages**  \n   - Water (plain or sparkling)  \n   - Unsweetened tea and coffee  \n   - Bone broth  \n   - Almond or coconut milk (unsweetened)  \n\n6. **Snacks and Treats** (in moderation)  \n   - Dark chocolate (at least 70% cocoa)  \n   - Keto-friendly desserts made with almond flour, coconut flour, or sugar substitutes  \n   - Pork rinds or keto-friendly protein bars  \n\n---\n\n### **Foods to Avoid on the Keto Diet**\n1. **High-Carb Foods**  \n   - Grains: wheat, rice, oats, barley, quinoa  \n   - Starchy vegetables: potatoes, sweet potatoes, corn, peas  \n   - Legumes: beans, lentils, chickpeas  \n\n2. **Sugary Foods**  \n   - Candy, cakes, cookies, pastries  \n   - Sugary drinks: soda, juice, sweetened teas  \n\n3. **Fruits** (except in small amounts)  \n   - High-sugar fruits: bananas, grapes, mangoes, pineapples  \n   - Dried fruits: raisins, dates, apricots  \n\n4. **Processed Foods**  \n   - Packaged snacks, chips, and crackers  \n   - Foods with added sugars or refined carbohydrates  \n\n5. **Certain Oils and Fats**  \n   - Vegetable oils: soybean oil, canola oil, corn oil, sunflower oil  \n\n---\n\n### **Sample Keto Meal Plan**\n**Breakfast:** Scrambled eggs cooked in butter with spinach and avocado.  \n**Lunch:** Grilled salmon with a side of roasted Brussels sprouts and a drizzle of olive oil.  \n**Snack:** A handful of almonds or celery sticks with cream cheese.  \n**Dinner:** Chicken thighs with cauliflower rice and creamy keto alfredo sauce.  \n**Dessert:** A square of dark chocolate or keto-friendly cheesecake.  \n\n---\n\n### **Tips for Success**\n1. Track your macros (carbohydrates, protein, and fat) to stay within your daily limits.  \n2. Stay hydrated and replenish electrolytes (sodium, potassium, magnesium).  \n3. Gradually reduce carbs to avoid \"keto flu\" symptoms.  \n4. Focus on whole, nutrient-dense foods rather than processed keto products.  \n\nAlways consult with a healthcare professional before starting any new diet, especially if you have underlying health conditions.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
